# React component and hook rules

This file consolidates official React guidance (purity, effects, JSX/hook call patterns). Use it when writing or reviewing UI and hooks.

---

## 1. Components and hooks must be pure

Canonical: [Components and Hooks must be pure](https://react.dev/reference/rules/components-and-hooks-must-be-pure) · [Keeping Components Pure](https://react.dev/learn/keeping-components-pure)

### What “pure” means

- **Idempotent:** Same inputs (props, state, context; hook arguments) → same result. Avoid non-idempotent work **during render** (`new Date()`, `Math.random()`, `fetch`, globals, `document.title`, etc.) — use **event handlers**, **effects**, or **`useState(() => …)`** lazy init as in the docs.
- **No side effects in render:** Observable work belongs in **handlers** or **effects** (`useEffect` / `useLayoutEffect` for external systems), not during the render phase.
- **Do not mutate non-local values during render:** No mutating module scope, props, state snapshots, hook args/returns, or objects already referenced in JSX.

### Allowed

- **Local mutation** of values **created in that render** (e.g. `const items = []; … push`) is fine.
- **Lazy initialization** without cross-component leaks, per docs.

### Immutability

- **Props / state:** never in-place mutation; copy or use setters.
- **Hook arguments and returns:** immutable after use; copy before changes.
- **After JSX:** don’t mutate objects already passed into JSX in the same render.

### Repo note

- Prefer **derive during render** over effect-sync for non-external state (Vercel **`rerender-derived-state-no-effect`**; details in [§3](#3-you-might-not-need-an-effect)).
- Flag render-time I/O, globals, DOM writes, prop/state mutation as **high** unless moved to handlers/effects.

