## 3. You Might Not Need an Effect

Canonical: [You Might Not Need an Effect](https://react.dev/learn/you-might-not-need-an-effect) · [Synchronizing with Effects](https://react.dev/learn/synchronizing-with-effects) (when an effect *is* appropriate)

Effects are for **synchronizing with an external system** (network, DOM widget, non-React store). If there is **no external system**, you usually **should not** use `useEffect` to mirror props/state into more state—that causes **extra renders**, **cascading updates**, and bugs.

### Prefer these instead of “sync” effects

| Situation | Prefer |
|-----------|--------|
| Value derivable from props/state | **Compute during render** (no new state; avoid redundant state) |
| Expensive **pure** derivation | **`useMemo`** — not `useEffect` + `setState` |
| Reset **whole** subtree when an id/key changes | **`key={...}`** on the inner component to reset state |
| User caused it (click, submit, typing action) | **Event handler** — not an effect “watching” state |
| Parent must stay in sync with child | **Lift state up** or **same event** updates both — not child `useEffect` calling parent `setState` |
| External store (browser API, non-React subscription) | **`useSyncExternalStore`** when applicable — not manual `useEffect` subscribe + `setState` |

### Data fetching in this repo

Prefer **TanStack Query** (`services/` hooks, server prefetch) and **RSC/async server components** over ad-hoc `useEffect`+`fetch`. If you use an effect for fetch, you need **cleanup** (race / stale response) per the docs—Query handles this pattern for client cache.

### Review flags

- **`useEffect` that only** `setState`s from props/other state → **Major**: derive or reshape state ([recap](https://react.dev/learn/you-might-not-need-an-effect)).
- **Chains of effects** each updating state to trigger the next → **Major**: compute in render and/or **one event handler** updates all needed state.
- **POST / mutations** triggered by effect on state that really means “user submitted” → **Major**: move to **submit handler**.
